    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3601890650" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3601890650" />
    <a title="Elena Sala" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58119141-elena-sala"><img alt="Elena Sala" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1469638554p2/58119141.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3601890650?book_show_action=true">Dec 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elena Sala" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elena Sala" href="/user/show/58119141-elena-sala">Elena Sala</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/58119141-elena-sala?shelf=european-contemporary">european-contemporary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/58119141-elena-sala?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/58119141-elena-sala?shelf=eastern-europe">eastern-europe</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3601890650" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17838097023388686534">THE BRIDGE ON THE DRINA (first published in Serbo-Croat in 1945) is not really a novel in the usual sense; rather it is a chronicle of sorts which recounts the story of the birth and death of Ottoman civilization as experienced by the people of Bosnia. The bridge in question, which is actually the main &quot;character &quot; of this book, was built at Višegrad on the Bosnia-Serbian frontier by a grand vizier of the Ottoman Empire in the 16th century. The whole narrative is woven around the unifying subjec</span>
  <span id="freeText17838097023388686534" style="display:none">THE BRIDGE ON THE DRINA (first published in Serbo-Croat in 1945) is not really a novel in the usual sense; rather it is a chronicle of sorts which recounts the story of the birth and death of Ottoman civilization as experienced by the people of Bosnia. The bridge in question, which is actually the main "character " of this book, was built at Višegrad on the Bosnia-Serbian frontier by a grand vizier of the Ottoman Empire in the 16th century. The whole narrative is woven around the unifying subject of that elegant, beautiful stone bridge, with its terrace and benches, the focal point of the lives of the people of Višegrad during three and a half turbulent centuries.<br /><br />The famous bridge was commissioned in 1572 by the Grand Vizier Mehmet Pasha. This Grand Vizier was no Ottoman, though. His title and name are somewhat misleading. Originally, he was one of a group of young Christian boys abducted from his mountain village in Bosnia and sent to Istanbul for a life of service for the sultan. The abduction of children for the purpose of serving the sultan seems to have been a regular practice at the time, not an extraordinary event. <br /><br />The boy was about ten years old when he was seized from his mother and although the whole experience must have been traumatic, he managed to achieve a brilliant career. The story of how the bridge was built was completely historical. The construction of the bridge across the river emanated from Grand Vizier's desire to be remembered in the place of his birth.<br /><br /> The rest of the book is a fictionalized history of all that happened on that bridge. Andrić does not focus on a single story, rather he offers us a chronicle of life in the heart of the Balkans. His narrative recounts the complex relationship between the occupying Turks, the local Bosnian Muslims and the local Bosnian Serbs. With the fall of the Ottoman Empire in the 19th century, Bosnia and the adjacent province of Herzegovina were placed under an Austrian protectorate, and later, these two provinces were annexed to the Hapsburg crown. This precipitated a crisis, a prologue to World War I which was finally sparked by the assassination of the Archduke Ferdinand in Sarajevo. The bridge on the Drina became one of the first casualties of this war.<br /><br />THE BRIDGE ON THE DRINA requires some previous knowledge about the history of the Balkans in general. It is a fascinating, masterfully crafted book, however, it will not appeal to the casual reader because it has none of the plot devices of a novel. Ivo Andrić won the Nobel Prize for Literature, hopefully this fact will lure some readers to do the homework required to read this ambitious masterpiece.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17838097023388686534" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

